1. Dramatic decline in job satisfaction

The data

The cities-job-satisfaction.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different cities around the world. In this data it was measured which proportion of people reported that they were unsatisfied with their work situation this year compared to last year. Each data point is a different city, and the value indicates the proportion of dissatisfied workers.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

You can clearly see in this plot that people are dramatically more dissatisfied at work this year compared to last year. I have used transparency for the dots to prevent overplotting/oversaturation, so this means that the entire dark area has an even amount of cities throughout. In other words, there are as many cities that increased from ~0% to ~40% dissatisfaction as there are cities that stayed around 0%. That's atrocious!

Question 1.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

Mistakes in the plot:

  1. Misleading use of transparency: The claim that "the entire dark area has an even amount of cities throughout" is incorrect. Transparency stacking in scatter plots does not work this way - darker areas indicate overlapping points, not uniform distribution. The dark region appears because many points cluster near the diagonal (y=x line), not because cities uniformly increased from ~0% to ~40%.

  2. Missing reference line: Without a diagonal reference line (y=x), it's difficult to assess whether satisfaction changed. Points on this line would indicate no change between years.

  3. Misleading title: The title "Dramatic increase in job dissatisfaction" is not supported by the data.

Correct interpretation:

When examining the data, most cities cluster near the diagonal line where this_year last_year, meaning job dissatisfaction levels remained relatively stable year-over-year. There is no dramatic increase - the data shows that most cities have similar dissatisfaction proportions in both years. The apparent "dark area" in the upper region is an artifact of point overlap near the diagonal, not evidence of widespread increases in dissatisfaction.

2. I will keep raising wages for all

The data

The wages.csv dataset contains (fictional) data from different companies in the city where I have been the mayor for the last few years. Each datapoint represents the average salary at a company. All the major companies in this city were surveyed both before I was elected and after a few years of my governing. However, this is not paired data, some companies are different from "before" and "after", so you do not need to do a paired analysis.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

As you can see, I have been able to produce a significant increase in the average salary for workers in my city. This high raise almost certainly entails that all (or almost all) workers are receiving a higher payment than what they were before I started to govern. But since I know you are going to ask me for more robust estimates, I have also provided the median increase (which is even more notable) and the number of workers in each group (so that you can see that the samples are balanced).

Question 2.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

Mistakes in the plots:

  1. Hiding the distribution: Bar charts showing only mean and median hide the underlying distribution of the data. Summary statistics alone can be misleading when the data has complex structure.

  2. Bimodal distribution in "after" data: The "after" wages data is bimodal - there are two distinct groups: one earning ~10-15 and another earning ~30-40. This means some workers actually earn LESS than before (when wages were ~15-25), while others earn much more.

  3. Misleading claim about "all workers": The claim that "all (or almost all) workers are receiving a higher payment" is false. The bimodal distribution shows that roughly half the workers in the "after" group earn less than the typical "before" wage.

Correct interpretation:

While the mean and median wages did increase, this hides a critical fact: the wage distribution after the policy change is bimodal. Some workers now earn significantly more (~30-40), but others earn less (~10-15) than the typical pre-policy wage (~15-25). The policy appears to have created wage inequality rather than uniformly raising wages for all workers. A visualization showing the full distribution (such as a violin plot, box plot, or strip plot) would reveal this important pattern.

%%R -w 600 -h 200 --res 150
# Load wages data
wages <- read_csv('data/wages.csv', show_col_types = FALSE)

# Plot 1: Mean salary bar chart (horizontal)
# X-axis does NOT start from 0, Y-axis sorted with before on top
wages %>%
    group_by(when) %>%
    summarise(mean_salary = mean(salary)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = mean_salary, y = factor(when, levels = c('after', 'before')), fill = when)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::dollar_format(), breaks = seq(16, 24, by = 2)) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(15, 25)) +
    labs(
        x = 'salary',
        y = 'when'
    ) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(legend.position = 'none')

3. Guns to the people

The data

The guns-r-us.csv dataset contains yearly data for the number of murders by firearms in Florida.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

As you can see, just after the gun law in Florida was enacted, deaths from firearms plummeted. I don't really think there is much else to discuss here.

Question 3.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

Mistakes in the plot:

  1. Inverted Y-axis: The most egregious error is that the Y-axis is inverted - high values are at the bottom and low values at the top. This makes an increase in deaths appear as a decrease.

  2. Visual deception with red fill: The red area fill, combined with the inverted axis, creates a visual illusion of "blood dripping down" that suggests deaths are decreasing when they are actually increasing after 2005.

  3. Misleading interpretation of the law's effect: The claim that "deaths from firearms plummeted" after the gun law is false. Looking at the actual data, deaths decreased from 2005 to 2007 but then increased significantly from 2007 onwards, reaching higher levels than before the law.

Correct interpretation:

This is a famous example of misleading visualization (similar to the Reuters gun deaths chart). When the Y-axis is properly oriented (0 at bottom), the data shows that after the "Stand Your Ground" law was enacted in 2005, firearm murders initially decreased slightly but then increased substantially from 2007 to 2012, reaching levels comparable to the early 1990s. The law did not cause a sustained decrease in firearm deaths - if anything, deaths increased in the years following its enactment.

# Load gun deaths data
guns = pd.read_csv('data/guns-r-us.csv')

# Recreate the misleading plot with inverted y-axis
area = alt.Chart(guns).mark_area(
    color='darkred',
    line={'color': 'black'}
).encode(
    x=alt.X('Year:O', title='Year'),
    y=alt.Y('Firearm murders:Q', 
            title='Number of murders involving firearms',
            scale=alt.Scale(reverse=True))
)

# Add vertical line for the law enactment (2005)
rule = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame({'Year': [2005]})).mark_rule(
    color='black',
    strokeWidth=2
).encode(
    x='Year:O'
)

# Add text annotation
text = alt.Chart(pd.DataFrame({'Year': [2005], 'y': [200], 'text': ['2005\nFlorida enacted\nits "Stand Your\nGround" law']})).mark_text(
    align='left',
    dx=5,
    fontSize=10
).encode(
    x='Year:O',
    y=alt.Y('y:Q', scale=alt.Scale(reverse=True)),
    text='text:N'
)

(area + rule + text).properties(
    title='Gun deaths in Florida',
    width=500,
    height=400
)

My approval ratings are astronomical

The data

The (fictional) state-comparison.csv dataset contains a sample of voters from my state and a neighboring state of similar socioeconomic standard. Voters in each state were asked to rate their approval of the state's mayor on a scale from 0 - 10,000.

My plots

Altair

ggplot

My claim

My approval ratings are through the roof! I am clearly doing a better job than my colleague and competitor next doors. And as you can see we sampled enough people to get smooth curves, which means that this difference is both likely to be statistically significant and the magnitude is just too big to ignore. There seems to be a few bores on the lower end of the spectrum, but can't win them all I guess. Do you want a 10k approval rating future? Vote Ostblom in 2020!

Question 4.1

rubric={reasoning:2,writing:1}

  • Explain which mistakes (if any) I have done in my plot and provide an interpretation of the data that is more correct than mine. Be brief and clear in your answer.
  • You might have some ideas just from looking at my plot, but you will likely need to do some investigation yourself to answer this question fully. You can reference your improved plot as needed.

Mistakes in the plot:

  1. Using KDE on tiny sample size: The most critical error is using a kernel density estimate (KDE) on an extremely small sample - only 3 data points per group! KDE creates smooth curves that suggest large sample sizes and continuous distributions, which is completely misleading here.

  2. False impression of statistical significance: The smooth curves create an illusion that there's enough data to draw meaningful conclusions about the distribution shape, when in reality we have almost no data.

  3. Hiding the actual data: The actual data points are:

    • My state: 1000, 9900, 10000
    • Neighboring states: 1000, 4100, 10000

    Both groups have the same minimum (1000) and maximum (10000), with only the middle value differing. The medians are actually quite similar.

Correct interpretation:

With only 3 data points per group, no meaningful statistical comparison can be made. The KDE smoothing creates artificial "distributions" that don't represent real data patterns. A proper visualization would show the actual data points directly (e.g., strip plot or dot plot), making it clear that we have very limited data. The claim of "smooth curves" indicating sufficient sampling is false - the smoothness comes from the KDE algorithm, not from having many data points.

# Original plot from Altair Gallery
# URL: https://altair-viz.github.io/gallery/simple_scatter_with_errorbars.html

import altair as alt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Generate sample data
np.random.seed(42)
x = np.arange(1, 8)
y = np.random.randn(7).cumsum()
y_err = np.random.uniform(0.5, 1.5, 7)

source = pd.DataFrame({
    'x': x,
    'y': y,
    'y_err': y_err
})

# Original simple scatter with error bars
points = alt.Chart(source).mark_point().encode(
    x='x:Q',
    y='y:Q'
)

errorbars = alt.Chart(source).mark_errorbar().encode(
    x='x:Q',
    y=alt.Y('y:Q'),
    yError='y_err:Q'
)

points + errorbars

In[107]:
# Improved version with communication enhancements

# Improvement 1: Better axis titles and chart title
# Improvement 2: Larger point size and color for visibility
# Improvement 3: Proper figure dimensions
# New parameter: tooltip for interactivity (not discussed in lectures)

points_improved = alt.Chart(source).mark_point(
    size=100,
    color='steelblue',
    filled=True
).encode(
    x=alt.X('x:Q', title='Measurement Day', axis=alt.Axis(tickMinStep=1)),
    y=alt.Y('y:Q', title='Cumulative Change'),
    tooltip=[
        alt.Tooltip('x:Q', title='Day'),
        alt.Tooltip('y:Q', title='Value', format='.2f'),
        alt.Tooltip('y_err:Q', title='Error', format='.2f')
    ]
)

errorbars_improved = alt.Chart(source).mark_errorbar(
    color='steelblue',
    thickness=2,
    ticks=alt.MarkConfig(color='steelblue', size=10)
).encode(
    x='x:Q',
    y=alt.Y('y:Q'),
    yError='y_err:Q'
)

(points_improved + errorbars_improved).properties(
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Weekly Measurement Trends with Uncertainty',
        subtitle='Error bars show measurement uncertainty range',
        fontSize=16,
        subtitleFontSize=12,
        subtitleColor='gray'
    ),
    width=500,
    height=350
).configure_axis(
    labelFontSize=12,
    titleFontSize=14
)
Out[107]:

Changes made to improve the plot for communication:

  1. Added descriptive axis titles and chart title with subtitle: The original plot had generic axis labels ('x' and 'y'). I added meaningful titles ('Measurement Day', 'Cumulative Change') and a main title with a subtitle explaining what the error bars represent. This helps viewers immediately understand what the data shows.

  2. Increased point size and added color: The original points were small and black. I increased the size to 100 and used a distinct color (steelblue) with filled=True to make the data points more visible and easier to track.

  3. Set proper figure dimensions: Added explicit width (500) and height (350) to ensure the plot has appropriate proportions for presentation, rather than relying on default sizing.

  4. Increased font sizes: Used configure_axis() to increase label and title font sizes (12 and 14 respectively) for better readability.

New parameter not discussed in lectures:

I used the tooltip parameter in the encode section. This adds interactive tooltips that appear when hovering over data points, showing the day number, exact value (formatted to 2 decimal places), and the error value. This is particularly useful for:

  • Allowing viewers to explore exact values without cluttering the chart
  • Providing additional context on demand
  • Making the visualization more engaging and interactive

The tooltip uses alt.Tooltip() with custom titles and number formatting (format='.2f'), which makes the hover information clear and professional.
